    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-14T18:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-14T18:36:00-05:00" n="903"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d903">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/13180.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-14T17:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 14, 1914, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In a friendly interview with the First Chief to-day he informed me that he was
                    now in open rupture with Zapata and did not desire an interview with him. He
                    stated that the two envoys imprisoned a week ago would continue prisoners and
                    that he would imprison any other emissaries from Zapata who might enter this
                    city. Under the circumstances, a conference with Zapata would not have the
                    approval of Carranza and would therefore be futile. I believe an agreement could
                    have been easily reached at one time had not Carranza persisted in his own
                    efforts. Carothers thinks that Villa will not approve of armed conflict with
                    Zapata.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Silliman</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
